    <div class="more_question_list">
        <a data-toggle="collapse" href="#more_question_4"><h4>WHAT ARE THE FOUR TYPES OF PLAGIARISM?</h4></a>
        <div id="more_question_4" class="collapse">
            <p lang="en-US" align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0.28cm; line-height: 150%">
                <font face="Arial" style="font-size: 12pt;">
                    Plagiarism comes in different ways and forms, and should be avoided by all means because of the serious consequences it poses. There are different types of plagiarism but we will focus on the four major types of plagiarism:<br/>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                        Direct Plagiarism:  This occurs when you copy a part of someone’s work in its totality and use it for your work without giving the copied work the proper citation. Here the exact same words are used without citing the source of the information. This is the worst kind of plagiarism and should be avoided. This is why it is important to run your work through a plagiarism checker before submitting.</li>
                        <li>
                        Self plagiarism: Self plagiarism is when someone copies their previously  submitted work without the permission of persons involved in that work. It is most frequent in students turning in a work already done by them without the permission of professors involved in that work.</li>
                        <li>
                        Accidental Plagiarism: Here, the plagiarism is not intended but it still carries the same consequences. It happens when someone unintentionally or neglects to quote the source of the information they used  or uses the same kind of words and phrases without proper citation. A good plagiarism checker can be used to identify any plagiarized content in your work for proper citation.</li>
                        <li>
                        Source based plagiarism: This can occur in different ways. It can be as a result of citing a wrong or non existent source  or when all the sources used for a work are not entirely captured in the references given in the work. It can also come in the form of data fabrication.
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                  
                </font>
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>


