    <div class="more_question_list">
        <a data-toggle="collapse" href="#more_question_7"><h4>WHAT PERCENTAGE OF SIMILARITY IS ACCEPTABLE?</h4></a>
        <div id="more_question_7" class="collapse">
            <p lang="en-US" align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0.28cm; line-height: 150%">
                <font face="Arial" style="font-size: 12pt;">
                        First, it is instructive to state that plagiarism and similarity are both different things and shouldn't be confused with each other.  Plagiarism involves copying some one's work without giving them the credit by quotation or citation, while similarity includes common word, terms and phrases that might be found in a particular work.<br/>
                        Just like plagiarism, there is no consensus on the acceptable rate of similarity to be allowed in a work, however most opinions are that it is more difficult to avoid similarity than it is to avoid plagiarism. It is almost impossible to completely avoid similar words and phrases especially where such words are popular online. Most persons have pegged the acceptable similarity at 20 to 25 % however the lesser the similarity, the better and more accurate your work will be.  To detect similarity in your work, use a plagiarism scanner to check the work before submitting. The plagiarism checker will indicate how many percent of your work is either plagiarized or similar in text to other works, thereby giving you the opportunity to correct . To avoid incidences of similarity, try to paraphrase your work as much as you can to reduce the chances of similarity.
                        
                </font>
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="more_question_list">
        <a data-toggle="collapse" href="#more_question_8"><h4>WHAT ARE THE 10 TYPES OF PLAGIARISM?</h4></a>
        <div id="more_question_8" class="collapse">
            <p lang="en-US" align="justify" style="margin-bottom: 0.28cm; line-height: 150%">
                <font face="Arial" style="font-size: 12pt;">
                        Plagiarism is a popular syndrome for persons that interact with a lot of writing examples, including teachers, students, professors and so on. There are different types of plagiarism and a plagiarism scanner can be used to detect most of them. However, we will be looking at 10 most common types of plagiarism:<br/>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                Clone plagiarism : This is most popular and perhaps the worst kind of plagiarism. Here, there is a verbatim replication of someone's work with little or no changes, and no proper citation and reference is given to the work copied .
                            </li>
                            <li>
                            Error plagiarism (404 error): This occurs where someone quotes an incorrect or non existent source as their references. It is usually impossible to trace such citations because it will lead to non existing sources.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                            Self plagiarism : This type of plagiarism is also common. It happens when someone copies their former work without giving it proper citation.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                            Hybrid plagiarism : Here, information is copied from well cited sources but no reference is given to all the information copied. The writer now presents the copied work as a new one.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                            Find and replace plagiarism : The trick here is to make changes in the  major  keywords and phrases with closely related words, without necessarily changing the whole idea in the context.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                            Remix plagiarism : This kind of plagiarism occurs where a writer copies ideas from different places and puts them all together in a way that is fit and understandable, then claims the work to be his own idea.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                            Aggregator plagiarism : Here, the writer includes the correct references and citations of where he got ideas from, but the problem with this is that the work is almost made up of someone else's idea and lacks originality.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                            Mashup plagiarism : This type of plagiarism occurs when the writer copies information from lots of sources, joins them together in his own document without properly citing or referencing the various sources.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                            Data falsification : When a writer tampers with the data obtained from another source with the intention of misleading the public, then it is plagiarism. Any such alteration should be duly notified to the appropriate authorities.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                            Inaccurate authorship: Here, a person that contributed to the success of a work does not get credit for work done, or in some instances, a person that did not contribute to the work gets credit for it.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        All these incidences of plagiarism can be reasonably avoided if the work is checked through a plagiarism scanner.  
                </font>
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

